<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="161" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,513,151,176]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[527,708,151,176]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyburni">
<emphasis box="[527,708,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia pyburni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to northwestern 
<taxonomicName box="[1065,1183,151,176]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="10" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[1360,1431,151,176]" name="Brazil" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,269,188,213]" name="Venezuela" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[328,441,188,213]" name="Colombia" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, where it is known from the Negro– 
<collectingRegion box="[847,929,188,212]" country="Colombia" name="Vaupes" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Vaupés</collectingRegion>
river systems and Neblina region (
<figureCitation box="[1323,1391,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1113,1135]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,189,1086]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,179,1091]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distribution of examined material of Amapasaurus tetradactylus, B. panoplia, B. peruana, B. pyburni, B. remota, B. scolecoides, and B. trisanale. Records of Bachia didactyla and B. scaea were obtained from the literature." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581978/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[151,222,223,248]" name="Brazil" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, it occurs only in the state of 
<collectingRegion box="[553,675,224,248]" country="Venezuela" name="Amazonas" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[685,859,223,248]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyburni">
<emphasis box="[685,859,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia pyburni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is fossorial and diurnal, inhabits both highland and lowland terra firme forests, where it is found in the soil and amid decaying roots (Kizirian &amp; McDiarmid 1998).
</paragraph>
